pr_review_comment_body:
On Mon, Mar 23, 2015 at 01:37:56AM -0700, pbrunet wrote:
> > +
> > +    namespace bisect {
> > +        template <class X, class A>
> > +            size_t bisect(X const& x, A const& a, long lo, long hi) {
> > +                if(hi<0) hi = x.end() - x.begin();
> > +                return std::upper_bound(x.begin()+lo, x.begin()+hi, a) - x.begin();
> > +            }
> > +
> > +        PROXY_IMPL(pythonic::bisect, bisect);
> > +
> > +    }
> > +
> > +}
> > +
> > +#endif
> > +
> 
> I choose this to break dependencies between files and classes.
> Usually, we create .hpp and .cpp files in a c++ project but it is not done here because we want to keep inlining as much as possible. I don't see any other solution to both keep inlining and correct file dependencies like in other c++ project.

There 's something I'm missing here: in that case you should have the
impl include the header and not the following, so that we can include
the header without getting the impl?

I think your implementation is cleaner, but I ended up writing this out to see.

```python
def copy(self, **overrides):
    defaults = {
        'db': self.db, 
        'execution_context': self.execution_context, 
        'state_root': self.state_root,
    }
    kwargs = merge(defaults, overrides)
    return type(self)(**kwargs)
```

I would find this huge switch statement easier to reason about if multiple items with the same result were grouped together:

```python
Artifact = config_pb2.Artifact
if artifact_type in (Artifact.GAPIC, Artifact.GAPIC_ONLY):
    pipeline_name = 'GapicClientPipeline'
elif artifact_type in (Artifact.GRPC, Artifact.GRPC_COMMON):
    pipeline_name = 'GrpcClientPipeline'
elif artifact_type == Artifact.GAPIC_CONFIG:
    pipeline_name = 'GapicConfigPipeline'
else:
    raise ValueError('Unrecognized artifact.')
```

You might:
```python
@classmethod
@memoized_method
def _get_build_flags(cls, target, build_flags_from_option, is_flagged):
```

This will get called twice for each invalid target, once by the fp strategy, once by the work loop in execute.

the linter will probably have some suggestions.

A general rule-of-thumb that the linter doesn't enforce is: opening and closing brackets, parens, etc should 'line up' with the same level of indentation.

E.g.

```javascript
  }).then(
    // dispatch newly created user
    newUser => store.dispatch('ADD_USER', _stateUser(newUser)),
    // send back error if necessary
    error => error
  );
```

not 

```javascript
  }).then(
      // dispatch newly created user
      newUser => store.dispatch('ADD_USER', _stateUser(newUser)),
      // send back error if necessary
      error => error
    );
```

because the opening `.then(` and closing `);` both should have 2 spaces.

For an example relevant here, see: https://github.com/learningequality/kolibri/blob/develop/kolibri/plugins/learn/assets/src/actions.js#L85
